Here is how you can do this in Julia:

```julia
function timezone_bumper(dt::DateTime; bump=3)
    return dt + Hour(bump)
end

function timezone_bumper(d::Date,; bump=3)
    throw(ArgumentError("This function only works for DateTime types, not Date types"))
end
```
In the first function `timezone_bumper(dt::DateTime)`, we simply add the number of hours to the provided DateTime. In the second function `timezone_bumper(d::Date; bump=3)`, an error is thrown since this function only works with DateTime types and not Date types.
